SECTION 1: DTCC OVERVIEW & BUSINESS CONTEXT (5 pages)
1.1 What is DTCC? (1 page)
History & Mission

Founded 1973 as central securities depository
$100+ trillion assets under custody (2025)
Critical infrastructure for U.S. capital markets
Post-trade processing backbone
DTCC Subsidiaries Relevant to Transfer Agents

DTC (Depository Trust Company) - central securities depository
NSCC (National Securities Clearing Corporation) - clearance
DTCC Solutions - technology services
Industry Position

Processes 98% of U.S. securities transactions
Connects 50,000+ financial institutions globally
Systemic importance to financial stability
1.2 What is FAST? (1 page)
Fast Automated Securities Transfer Program

Contract between DTC and transfer agents
Transfer agents act as custodians for DTC
Eliminates physical certificate movement
Introduced 1975, now 100+ agents managing 1.1M+ issues
FAST Balance Certificate System

Balance certificate represents DTC's position
Book-entry movements without physical certificates
Daily position reconciliation requirements
Connection via PTS/PBS or ANIRA systems
Benefits of FAST Participation

Dematerialization of securities
Reduced printing and shipping costs
Faster transaction settlement
Lower operational risk
1.3 What is DRS? (1 page)
Direct Registration System

Allows investors to hold shares directly with issuer (book-entry)
Alternative to physical certificates or "street name" brokerage holdings
Investor receives periodic statements, not certificates
Electronic transfer between transfer agent and broker/dealer
DRS Profile System

Broker requests transfer from DRS account to DTC
Requires validated proprietary account information
Surety or insurance coverage required
Real-time electronic processing
T+1 Settlement Compliance

Industry moved from T+2 to T+1 settlement (2024)
DRS critical infrastructure for faster settlement
Reduces settlement risk and market exposure
Platform for future dematerialization efforts
1.4 Why Transfer Agents Need DTCC Integration (1 page)
Regulatory Obligations

SEC Rule 17Ad-10: Transfer agent recordkeeping
Required for DTC-eligible securities
Facilitate efficient securities transfers
Support investor choice (certificated vs. book-entry)
Business Necessity

Cannot process DRS transfers without DTCC connectivity
Position reconciliation required daily
Corporate actions distribution
Competitive requirement (all major TAs are DTCC-connected)
Investor Expectations

Fast electronic transfers (not 7-10 day certificate shipping)
Flexibility to move between broker and direct registration
Real-time position visibility
Lower fees (no certificate printing/shipping costs)
1.5 Business Requirements for Tableicty (1 page)
Phase 1: Core DRS Transfers

Inbound: Broker â†’ Transfer Agent (investor wants direct registration)
Outbound: Transfer Agent â†’ Broker (investor wants to sell via broker)
Position inquiries and status updates
Phase 2: Position Reconciliation

Daily FAST balance reconciliation
Identify and resolve breaks
Automated reconciliation reporting
Phase 3: Corporate Actions

Dividend payment notifications
Stock split processing
Merger/acquisition communications
Proxy material distribution coordination
Gateway Expansion Requirements

Multi-tenant routing (support additional TAs)
Tenant-specific DTCC credentials
Isolated message queues per tenant
Tenant-level audit trails
SECTION 2: TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS (15 pages)
2.1 DTCC Connectivity Architecture (2 pages)
2.1.1 Connection Protocols
Option 1: PTS/PBS (Participant Terminal System/Browser System)

Web-based interface for manual operations
Used for setup, configuration, manual overrides
Not suitable for high-volume automated processing
Access requirements and authentication
Option 2: ANIRA (Agent Network for Internet Remote Access)

Broadband Internet connection option
RESTful APIs or file transfer
Suitable for small to medium agents
Lower infrastructure costs than mainframe
Option 3: Mainframe Connection

IBM MQ or Connect:Direct protocols
High-volume automated processing
Complex setup, higher infrastructure costs
Used by large transfer agents (Computershare, AST)
Option 4: DTCC API Marketplace (Modern)

RESTful APIs with JSON payloads
OAuth 2.0 or API key authentication
Real-time webhooks for notifications
INVESTIGATE: Availability for TA Services
Tableicty Recommendation: [TO BE DETERMINED]

Evaluation criteria: cost, scalability, complexity
Gateway-ready consideration: can we support multiple protocols?
Security posture analysis
Development timeline impact
