SECTION 3: SECURITY REQUIREMENTS (8 pages)
3.1 Authentication Architecture (2 pages)
3.1.1 mTLS (Mutual TLS) Certificate Management
Certificate Acquisition

DTCC Certificate Authority process
CSR (Certificate Signing Request) generation
Approval workflow and timeline
Installation and configuration
Certificate Specifications

Key algorithm: RSA 2048-bit or ECC P-256
Validity period: Typically 1-2 years
Subject DN requirements
Extended Key Usage extensions
Private Key Security

Generation: HSM vs. software-based
Storage: HashiCorp Vault with encryption
Access controls: Least privilege, role-based
Backup and recovery: Encrypted backups, escrow considerations
3.1.2 Certificate Lifecycle Management
Renewal Process

90-day advance notification
Automated renewal pipeline
Zero-downtime rotation strategy
Testing renewed certificates in sandbox
Revocation Scenarios

Compromise detection procedures
Emergency revocation process
DTCC notification requirements
Re-issuance timeline
Monitoring & Alerting

Expiration tracking (30, 60, 90 days)
Certificate validation checks
OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) responders
PagerDuty alerts for expiration/revocation
3.1.3 Multi-Tenant Certificate Strategy (Gateway-Ready)
Option A: Shared Certificate with Tenant Routing

Single Tableicty certificate for all tenants
Message routing based on tenant ID in payload
Pros: Simpler certificate management
Cons: No isolation at TLS layer
Option B: Certificate Per Tenant

Each gateway customer has own DTCC certificate
True isolation at authentication layer
Pros: Security isolation, independent lifecycle
Cons: Certificate management complexity, DTCC coordination
Recommendation: [TO BE DETERMINED AFTER DTCC CONSULTATION]

3.2 Encryption Requirements (2 pages)
3.2.1 Data in Transit
TLS Requirements

Minimum version: TLS 1.2 (prefer TLS 1.3)
Cipher suites: AES-256-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305
Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS) enabled
Certificate pinning for DTCC endpoints
Message-Level Encryption

Investigate: Does DTCC support end-to-end encryption beyond TLS?
Payload signing for non-repudiation
Timestamp validation to prevent replay attacks
3.2.2 Data at Rest
Database Encryption

AWS RDS encryption with KMS
Column-level encryption for PII (SSN, account numbers)
Transparent Data Encryption (TDE)
Message Queue Encryption

RabbitMQ encrypted at rest
Encrypted connections between middleware and queue
Log Encryption

Audit logs encrypted with rotation
Immutable log storage (WORM - Write Once Read Many)
Backup Encryption

Automated encrypted backups
Separate encryption keys for backups
Secure key escrow
3.2.3 Key Management Strategy
HashiCorp Vault Architecture

Encryption keys stored in Vault
Dynamic secrets generation
Automatic key rotation policies
Audit logging of all key access
Key Hierarchy

Master keys (HSM-protected)
Data encryption keys (DEK)
Key encryption keys (KEK)
Tenant-specific key namespaces
Key Rotation

Frequency: Quarterly for data keys, annually for master keys
Zero-downtime rotation procedures
Re-encryption of data with new keys
Versioning and rollback capability
3.3 Access Controls (2 pages)
3.3.1 Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
Role Definitions

Super Admin: Full system access, configuration changes
DTCC Operations: Can send/receive DTCC messages, view audit logs
Customer Service: Read-only shareholder data, view transaction status
Auditor: Read-only access to all logs and configurations
Tenant Admin: Manage own tenant's users and settings (gateway model)
