3.3.2 Authentication for Internal Users
JWT (JSON Web Token) Architecture

Token payload: user ID, roles, tenant ID, expiration
Signing algorithm: RS256 (asymmetric)
Token lifetime: 1 hour (short-lived)
Refresh token mechanism (30-day validity)
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

Required for Super Admin and DTCC Operations roles
TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) - Google Authenticator, Authy
Backup codes for MFA recovery
Hardware token support (YubiKey)
Session Management

Idle timeout: 30 minutes
Concurrent session limits per user
Force logout on role change
Audit trail of all logins/logouts
3.3.3 API Authentication
Service-to-Service Authentication

Mutual TLS between Django and Go middleware
API keys for external integrations
Service accounts with limited scope
API Rate Limiting

Per-user limits (100 requests/minute)
Per-tenant limits (1000 requests/minute)
DTCC message send limits (per DTCC SLA)
3.3.4 Network Access Controls
VPC Security Groups

Least privilege: Only required ports open
Source IP restrictions (no 0.0.0.0/0)
Separate security groups for each tier (web, app, database)
Bastion Host

SSH access only through bastion
MFA required for bastion login
Session recording for audit
Database Access

No direct internet access to RDS
Application access via private subnets only
Database firewall rules
3.4 Audit Logging (2 pages)
3.4.1 Regulatory Requirements
SEC Rule 17Ad-10: Transfer Agent Recordkeeping

Must maintain records of all securities positions
Record retention: Minimum 6 years (3 years easily accessible)
Audit trail of all changes to shareholder records
Immutable logs (cannot be altered or deleted)
SOC 2 Requirements (TSC CC7.2)

Logging of security-relevant events
Protection of log information
Timely investigation of anomalies
3.4.2 What to Log
DTCC Transaction Logging

Every message sent to DTCC (full payload)
Every message received from DTCC (full payload)
Timestamp (high precision, synchronized clock)
Transaction ID and correlation IDs
Success/failure status
Error messages and reason codes
Processing duration
Authentication Events

User login/logout (successful and failed attempts)
MFA verification events
Role changes and permission grants
API key creation/revocation
Certificate rotation events
Data Access Logging

Shareholder PII access (who, what, when)
Database queries that return sensitive data
File downloads and exports
Configuration changes
System Events

Service start/stop/restart
Configuration changes
Software deployments
Infrastructure changes (Terraform apply)
Error conditions and exceptions
3.4.3 Log Storage & Management
Centralized Logging Architecture

All logs sent to Wazuh SIEM
Structured JSON format
Correlation across services
Log Retention Policy

Hot storage: 90 days (Elasticsearch/OpenSearch)
Warm storage: 3 years (S3 Standard)
Cold storage: 3+ years (S3 Glacier)
Immutability: S3 Object Lock (Compliance mode)
Log Encryption

Encrypted in transit (TLS)
Encrypted at rest (S3-SSE or KMS)
Separate encryption keys from application data
3.4.4 Audit Trail Integrity
Tamper Detection

Cryptographic hashing (SHA-256) of log entries
Merkle tree or blockchain-inspired structure
Periodic integrity verification
Access Controls

Logs are write-only for applications
Read access restricted to auditors and security team
No delete permissions (immutable)
Alerting on Anomalies

Failed login attempts (5+ in 10 minutes)
Unusual data access patterns (bulk PII downloads)
DTCC transaction errors (spike in rejections)
System errors and crashes
SECTION 4: COMPLIANCE REQUIREMENTS (5 pages)
4.1 SEC Regulations (2 pages)
4.1.1 SEC Rule 17Ad-10: Recordkeeping
Covered Records

Securities position records (who owns what)
Transaction journals (all changes to positions)
Reconciliation records (daily FAST balance checks)
Corporate action records (dividends, splits, etc.)
Record Retention

Minimum: 6 years from creation
Immediately accessible: Most recent 3 years
Format: Original or reproducible copy
Index and retrieval system required
Tableicty Implementation

PostgreSQL database with 3-year hot retention
S3 archival for years 4-6
Full-text search capability
Automated retention policy enforcement
4.1.2 SEC Rule 17Ad-17: Lost Securityholder Program
Requirement: Attempt to contact lost shareholders
Relevance to DTCC Integration:
Return mail from DRS statements may indicate lost shareholder
Coordinate with DTCC on escheatment procedures
Implementation: Outside Phase 1 scope, document for future
4.1.3 Regulation S-P: Privacy of Consumer Financial Information
Scope: Protects shareholder PII

Requirements:

Privacy notice to shareholders
Opt-out mechanism for information sharing
Safeguards to protect customer information
Vendor management (ensure DTCC has adequate safeguards)
Tableicty Implementation

Encryption of PII at rest and in transit
Access controls (need-to-know basis)
Annual privacy policy review
Data breach response plan
4.1.4 SEC Form TA-1 and TA-2 Filings
Form TA-1: Application for registration as transfer agent

Tableicty must file before commencing operations
Lists DTCC connectivity as operational capability
Form TA-2: Annual report of transfer agent activities

Transaction volume statistics
Turnaround time metrics (must meet SEC standards)
DTCC integration enables automated metric collection
4.2 DTCC Operational Requirements (2 pages)
4.2.1 Service Level Agreements (SLAs)
Message Processing Timeframes

DRS Transfer: T+1 settlement (complete within 1 business day)
Position Reconciliation: Must reconcile by market open
Corporate Actions: Vary by action type (document specific SLAs)
Uptime Requirements

DTCC systems available: 99.9% during market hours
Planned maintenance windows (typically weekends)
Unplanned outage procedures
Tableicty SLA Commitments

Middleware availability: 99.95% (higher than DTCC requirement)
Message processing latency: <5 seconds (median)
Error rate: <0.1% (excluding rejections due to invalid data)
4.2.2 FAST Balance Reconciliation
Daily Reconciliation Process

Overnight batch: Compare TA records vs. DTCC balance certificate
Break identification and exception report
Resolution deadline: Before market open (9:30 AM ET)
Reconciliation Breaks

Common causes: Timing differences, unprocessed transactions, system errors
Resolution workflow: Investigate, correct root cause, resubmit
Escalation: Persistent breaks require DTCC investigation
Documentation Requirements

Maintain reconciliation reports for 6 years
Audit trail of break resolution
Exception reporting to management
4.2.3 Incident Reporting
When to Notify DTCC

System outage affecting DTCC connectivity (>1 hour)
Data breach potentially affecting DTC-eligible securities
Discovery of erroneous transactions
Notification Timeline

Critical incidents: Within 1 hour
Non-critical: Within 24 hours
Post-incident report: Within 5 business days
Tableicty Incident Response Plan

Incident detection (monitoring and alerting)
Assessment and classification
Containment and mitigation
DTCC notification (if required)
Root cause analysis and remediation
Post-mortem documentation
4.2.4 Business Continuity Planning
DTCC Expectations

Disaster recovery plan with <4 hour RTO (Recovery Time Objective)
Backup communication channels
Regular DR testing (at least annually)
Tableicty DR Architecture

Multi-AZ deployment (AWS availability zones)
Automated failover for critical components
Database backups: Continuous (RDS automated backups)
Middleware state: Stateless design (easy recovery)
Runbook for DTCC connectivity restoration
